deral Legislation with Quebec Civil Law -- tThe Canadian Ideal -- tThe Dangers of Secession in Democracy -- tSpeech on a Motion by the Opposition -- tLetter to Mr. Lucien Bouchard -- tLetter to Mr. Bernard Landry -- tLetter to Mr. Bernard Landry -- tWhy a Quebecer Wants to Keep British Columbia as Part of His Country -- tLetter to Mr. Jacques Brassard -- tBeyond Plan A and Plan B: The Two Debates on Canadian Unity -- tLetter to Mr. Claude Ryan -- tRespect for Democracy in Canada -- tThe Practical Difficulties of a Unilateral Secession -- tStatement in Response to the Ruling of the Supreme Court -- tLetter to Mr. Lucien Bouchard -- tThe International Community and the Secessionist Phenomenon0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSo begins this collection of Stéphane Dion's speeches from 1996 to 1998. Organized around four central themes, Straight Talk shows the breadth and strength of Dion's convictions. Dion believes that Canada is first and foremost a nation of caring people, in contrast to the image projected by the endless, dry constitutional debate. He argues that the melding of diversity and unity that is the basis of this nation is possible only because of the particular federalism that Canadians have invented. This federalism, however, is far from perfect and it is the responsibility of government to continue to work to improve it, always remembering that its core must be the quality of service it provides to Canadians. Dion believes that the Quebec question is not a constitutional question but one that concerns identity: many francophones believe that their identity and culture are not respected in the rest of Canada and see the anglophone majority as a force for assimilation, while many in other provinces feel that separatists do not share the same values of openness and tolerance. He believes strongly that the secession process the Parti Québecois has proposed - effecting independence on the basis of incorrect legal theory, an unclear referendum question, and a majority of fifty percent plus one - is difficult to reconcile with democracy and raises questions that must be discussed openly and resolved democratically. Straight Talk is a refreshingly honest and frank discussion about a matter that has been at the forefront of Canadian's thoughts for too many years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356788740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773567887423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773567887/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles